    "tldrSummary": "25+ note-taking apps tested for engineering workflows. Obsidian wins on privacy (Trust Score 92), Notion wins on integrations (91), Logseq wins for graph-based thinking. All support code blocks and Markdown.",
    "postContent": "Software engineers have note-taking requirements that general productivity tools handle poorly. You need proper code block formatting with syntax highlighting. You need version history that doesn't lose your architecture diagrams at the worst possible moment. You need fast search across months of technical notes, including code snippets. And increasingly, you need integration with the tools that define your actual workday: GitHub, Linear, your terminal, your browser's developer tools.\n\nWe tested 25+ note-taking apps specifically against an engineering use case. Here's what made the cut.\n\n## Why Most Note-Taking Apps Fail Engineers\n\nThe fundamental problem is that most note-taking apps are designed for prose, not for technical content. Markdown support helps, but it's not enough. Engineers write in a hybrid mode — prose explanations interwoven with code blocks, terminal outputs, API responses, and diagrams. A tool that handles this hybrid gracefully is worth far more than one with beautiful typography and no code support.\n\nWe evaluated each tool on five engineering-specific criteria: code block quality (syntax highlighting, language detection, line numbers), search across code content, integration with GitHub and issue trackers, support for diagrams (Mermaid, PlantUML, draw.io), and local-first or offline capability.\n\n## Best Note-Taking Apps for Engineers 2026\n\n### 1. Obsidian — Trust Score: 92 | Integration Score: 77\n\nObsidian earns the highest Trust Score of any note-taking tool we've tested because of its local-first architecture. Your notes live on your machine by default. There's no cloud account to breach, no vendor to subpoena, no server-side AI processing your architectural decisions. For engineers working on sensitive infrastructure, proprietary systems, or anything under NDA, this matters enormously.\n\nThe Markdown-native approach means code blocks are first-class citizens. The community plugin ecosystem adds Mermaid diagram support, Git integration for version control (your notes live in a repo, treated like code), and custom code execution environments. The graph view — showing connections between linked notes — is genuinely useful for mapping system architecture across multiple documents.\n\nThe Integration Score of 77 reflects the trade-off: local-first means fewer native integrations, though the community plugins bridge most gaps. Obsidian Sync (the optional paid sync) handles cross-device availability while keeping the architecture privacy-preserving.\n\n### 2. Notion — Trust Score: 87 | Integration Score: 91\n\nNotion's position on an engineering note-taking list might surprise people who associate it with project management, but engineers increasingly use it as their primary technical documentation layer. The reason is simple: the block-based editor handles mixed content — prose, code blocks, embeds, tables, linked databases — better than any other cloud-native tool.\n\nCode blocks support syntax highlighting for every major language. Database views can organize research notes, bug reports, and architecture documents with filters that would require a spreadsheet and three hours of manual work in any other tool. The Integration Score of 91 reflects deep GitHub embedding, Linear integration, and Slack connectivity.\n\n### 3. Logseq — Trust Score: 91 | Integration Score: 72\n\nLogseq is the engineer's alternative to Obsidian — also local-first, also Markdown-based, but with an outliner-first philosophy that suits engineers who think in hierarchical structures. Every note is a graph of bullet points, and queries let you pull information across your entire knowledge base using Datalog-style logic. For engineers who want to write custom queries against their own notes (\"show me all notes tagged #architecture from the last 30 days\"), Logseq is uniquely powerful.\n\nThe Trust Score of 91 reflects the same local-first privacy advantage as Obsidian. Your knowledge graph lives on your machine. The Integration Score of 72 reflects the trade-off — Logseq has fewer polished integrations than cloud-native tools.\n\n### 4. Notion AI / Bear (for Apple users) — Trust Score: 85 | Integration Score: 80\n\nBear remains the best native note-taking experience for engineers deep in the Apple ecosystem. The writing experience is outstanding, Markdown rendering is instantaneous, and the tagging system handles technical topics with elegant flexibility. Nested tags (like #architecture/microservices) give you enough structure without forcing a rigid folder hierarchy.\n\nFor Apple-platform engineers who don't need deep third-party integrations and prioritize a frictionless writing experience above all else, Bear is the daily driver we'd recommend without hesitation.\n\n### 5. Craft — Trust Score: 84 | Integration Score: 76\n\nCraft has become the premium alternative to Bear for Apple engineers who want a slightly more visual document format. The document linking system, daily notes feature, and export quality (particularly PDF and Markdown exports) are all best-in-class. The iCloud sync is seamless and the Mac app is a native citizen of macOS in a way that Electron-based apps never quite achieve.\n\n## GitHub Integration: The Differentiator\n\nFor engineering note-taking specifically, GitHub integration separates useful tools from essential ones. Obsidian with the Git plugin treats your entire vault as a repository — you can commit your notes, branch them for experiments, and review history through standard git commands. Notion embeds GitHub issue references natively. Logseq supports git sync.\n\nIf your notes about a system should live next to the code for that system, Obsidian's Git plugin is the most elegant implementation of that philosophy we've tested.\n\n## The AI Question\n\nEvery major note-taking tool now has an AI assistant. For engineers specifically, the AI features worth paying for are code explanation (paste a function, get a plain-English description), search-across-notes summarization, and meeting-to-action-items extraction. The AI features not worth paying for are AI-generated notes you didn't ask for, suggestions that interrupt your flow, and any feature that requires sending your code to a model endpoint you don't control.\n\nCheck the privacy documentation before enabling AI features. Several tools send note content to third-party model providers — this may violate your employment contract if you're taking notes about proprietary systems.\n\n## Bottom Line\n\nObsidian leads for privacy and local-first engineering workflows. Notion leads for team-shared technical documentation. Logseq leads for graph-based knowledge management. Bear and Craft lead for Apple-native simplicity. Your choice depends on whether you prioritize privacy or integration.",
    "verdictText": "Obsidian leads for privacy-conscious engineers with local-first architecture. Notion leads for team collaboration. Logseq leads for engineers who want queryable knowledge graphs. Bear leads for Apple-native simplicity.",
    "isLivingGuide": false,
