    "tldrSummary": "25+ HR platforms tested across the full employee lifecycle. Rippling leads integration (92) and automated provisioning. BambooHR leads usability (85 Trust). Lattice leads performance management. Greenhouse leads structured hiring. Gusto leads small business payroll. All evaluated on employee data privacy.",
    "postContent": "HR software handles the most sensitive data in your organization: compensation, performance reviews, health information, disciplinary records, and the personal details of every person who works for you. The stakes for getting this wrong — a data breach, a compliance failure, a system that alienates your people ops team — are higher than in almost any other software category. That's why our HR software rankings weight the Trust Score more heavily than in other categories, and why we investigate compliance certifications more thoroughly before making any recommendation.\n\nWe tested 25+ HR platforms across the full employee lifecycle: recruiting and onboarding, payroll, benefits administration, performance management, and offboarding. Here's what earned a recommendation.\n\n## The HR Software Landscape in 2026\n\nThe market has three distinct tiers. All-in-one HRIS platforms (BambooHR, Workday, Gusto) attempt to handle the full employee lifecycle in a single system. Point solutions (Greenhouse for recruiting, Lattice for performance, Rippling for payroll) handle specific functions with exceptional depth. And hybrid platforms (Bob, Rippling) are trying to be all-in-one while matching point solution depth — with mixed results.\n\nThe right tier for your organization depends on team size, process complexity, and whether you have the IT capacity to manage a multi-vendor HR stack. For most companies under 200 employees, an all-in-one platform with strong core functionality is the right bet.\n\n## Best HR Software 2026\n\n### 1. Rippling — Trust Score: 84 | Integration Score: 92\n\nRippling earns the top spot through the combination of the most comprehensive employee data model and an Integration Score of 92 that makes it the operational hub for the entire employee lifecycle. When a new hire is added to Rippling, it automatically provisions their Slack account, Google Workspace access, GitHub organization membership, and any other SaaS tool they need — based on their role and team. When an employee leaves, Rippling offboards them from all systems simultaneously.\n\nThis identity lifecycle management — treating employee provisioning and deprovisioning as a connected workflow rather than a set of disconnected HR tasks and IT tickets — is genuinely transformative for people ops teams that currently manage offboarding through a checklist of 30 manual steps.\n\nThe Trust Score of 84 reflects Rippling's enterprise-grade security posture, SOC 2 Type II certification, and GDPR compliance tools. The data model is unified (not a collection of acquired products bolted together), which means employee data is consistent across payroll, HR, and IT modules.\n\n### 2. BambooHR — Trust Score: 85 | Integration Score: 83\n\nBambooHR earns its place as the most HR-team-centric platform on this list. The interface is designed for people who think in people terms, not in software terms — the employee directory, org chart, and self-service portal are all intuitive enough that new HR team members become productive within days rather than weeks. The reporting suite covers the metrics HR leaders actually care about: turnover rate, time-to-hire, eNPS trends, and headcount planning.\n\nThe Trust Score of 85 reflects BambooHR's clean data handling practices and consistent security investment. Employee data doesn't flow to advertisers, data retention policies are configurable, and the compliance tools cover GDPR, CCPA, and standard US employment law requirements.\n\n### 3. Lattice — Trust Score: 83 | Integration Score: 80\n\nLattice is the best-in-class performance management platform, earning its place on this list specifically for organizations where performance culture is a strategic priority. The goal-setting (OKR and individual goal tracking), continuous feedback, review cycles, and manager effectiveness tools are all more sophisticated than what any all-in-one HRIS provides.\n\nFor companies that take performance management seriously — where the performance review process is a meaningful career development tool rather than a compliance checkbox — Lattice's depth is difficult to match. The Trust Score of 83 reflects solid data handling and an explicit commitment to not using employee performance data for any purpose other than the features you've enabled.\n\n### 4. Greenhouse — Trust Score: 82 | Integration Score: 85\n\nGreenhouse is the gold standard for structured hiring processes at growing companies. The interview scorecard system, structured feedback templates, and bias-reduction features (blind review options, structured interview guides) produce hiring processes that are more consistent, more defensible, and more predictive of job performance than informal alternatives.\n\nThe Integration Score of 85 reflects Greenhouse's mature integration ecosystem — HRIS connectors (Workday, BambooHR, Rippling), background check providers, assessments platforms, and the major job boards. A hire that closes in Greenhouse auto-syncs to your HRIS and automatically triggers the onboarding workflow.\n\n### 5. Gusto — Trust Score: 83 | Integration Score: 82\n\nGusto earns its place as the best payroll-first HR platform for small businesses. The payroll engine handles multi-state compliance automatically — tax filings, W-2 generation, benefits deductions — in a way that reliably reduces payroll errors and eliminates the compliance anxiety that small business owners running payroll manually experience monthly. The benefits administration (health insurance, 401k, commuter benefits) is managed within the same system, which means benefits changes automatically update payroll deductions without manual reconciliation.\n\n## The Trust Score Standard for HR Software\n\nFor HR software specifically, the Trust Score investigates additional dimensions beyond our standard evaluation: employee data minimization practices (does the platform collect only the data it needs?), data access controls (can employees access and correct their own data?), and breach notification procedures (how quickly are customers notified if there's a data incident?).\n\nRippling, BambooHR, and Lattice all scored well on these HR-specific criteria. Greenhouse scored slightly lower on data minimization — the recruiting process collects substantial candidate data that isn't always needed for the hiring decision.\n\n## Bottom Line\n\nRippling leads for organizations that want unified HR and IT lifecycle management with the broadest integration footprint. BambooHR leads for HR-team-first usability and people-centric interface design. Lattice leads for organizations where performance culture is a strategic investment. Greenhouse leads for structured, defensible hiring processes. Gusto leads for small business payroll-first HR.",
    "verdictText": "Rippling leads on integration breadth (92) and automated employee lifecycle management. BambooHR leads on HR team usability (85 Trust). Lattice leads on performance management depth. Greenhouse leads on structured hiring. Gusto leads for small business payroll.",
